article.description: Antawn Jamison and Gilbert Arenas each scored 18 points as the Golden State Warriors extended their winning streak to a season-best four games Wednesday night with a 108-94 victory over the undermanned Los Angeles Clippers.

related.description:
Los Angeles Clippers forward Elton Brand was scratched from the lineup Wednesday night against the Golden State
Warriors because of a bruised lower left leg.
related.linkText: Bruised leg forces Clippers' Brand to sit out
related.title: Brand misses Clippers' game against Warriors
related.headline: Brand misses Clippers' game against Warriors

article.headline: Warriors stay hot, in playoff hunt
article.linkText: Warriors rip Clippers for season-best win streak
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Clippers can only look at Golden State with amazement and envy. The Warriors' starting lineup has remained intact for the entire season. Two of those starters, Antawn Jamison and Gilbert Arenas, each scored 18 points as the Warriors extended their winning streak to a season-best four games Wednesday night with a 108-94 victory over the undermanned Los Angeles Clippers. All five Warriors starters -- including Troy Murphy, Erick Dampier and Jason Richardson -- scored in double figures for the seventh time this season. "That's impressive,'' Clippers reserve guard Eric Piatkowski said. "There's got to be a freak accident every now and then to keep somebody out of the starting five.'' The Clippers, meanwhile, have had 14 players start a game for them -- including Cherokee Parks, who made his first of the season at power forward for the injured Elton Brand and had five points and four rebounds in 16 minutes. Brand was scratched because of a bruised lower left leg. He was injured with about three minutes left in Tuesday night's loss to the Lakers when he fell trying to defend against one of Shaquille O'Neal's slam dunks. "It's ridiculous is what it is,'' Clippers coach Alvin Gentry said after his team's 12th loss in 15 games. "The whining and complaining part is long over. We've got to keep playing the guys who are healthy.'' Murphy had 11 points and 10 rebounds, helping the NBA's second-highest scoring team remain three games behind Phoenix for the eighth and final Western Conference playoff spot. It's the first time the Warriors have won four straight since Jan. 27-Feb. 4, 2000 -- and the first time they are within two games of .500 since starting out 1-3. "I think winning and chemistry go hand in hand,'' Murphy said. "I think that's something we lacked the last couple of years. This team definitely has chemistry, and it helps us share the ball a lot better.'' Richardson, the two-time slam dunk champion, brought oohs and aahs from the Staples Center crowd of 15,273 with a 360-degree tomahawk dunk over Quentin Richardson that gave the Warriors an 86-67 lead with 46 seconds left in the third and capped a 10-2 spurt. The Clippers never threatened thereafter. "We're just trying to improve,'' Jason Richardson said. "Guys have put the past behind us and we place the team first above individual goals. It does a lot for a team to have everyone's energy up, and we're still playing for the playoffs.'' Jamison, who had scored at least 20 points in his previous 11 games against the Clippers, led the Warriors to a 60-42 halftime lead with 13. Golden State opened the game with a 24-9 run. Dampier capped it with five straight points after swatting away a layup by Lamar Odom, who led the Clippers in the first half with 11 points and finished with 16. Bob Sura capped a 15-7 run with a pair of free throws and a 3-pointer that gave the Warriors their biggest lead of the half, 48-27, with 4:40 left in the second quarter. "It's been really frustrating the way everything has gone,'' Piatkowski said after the Clippers' 12th loss in 15 games. "It's amazing, how much better just getting one victory can make you feel when you wake up the next day. You don't have that horrible knot in your stomach and you feel a lot better about yourself. They say that winning cures all, and that's the truth.'' Maggette, whose recent play has resulted in fewer minutes for Piatkowski, missed seven of his first eight shots and finished 4-for-15 with 11 points.

Game notes
The Warriors have won five of their last seven road games. ... Golden State finished February 8-5 after going 8-7 in January. It's the first time the franchise has had consecutive winning months since the final four months of the 1993-94 season. ... The Warriors, who got a season-high 56 points from their bench on Monday at Denver, got 38 from the reserves against the Clippers. ... Brand has missed three games this season, two in December because of a strained right calf. ... Keyon Dooling missed his fourth game because of a strained left arch. ... Piatkowski recorded his 5,000th career point on a 3-pointer with 2:48 left in the first quarter.
